post_text:
To the Harbor Springs Community:
We want to clarify some rumors circulating regarding a spike in enrollment in our schools. There are currently 746 K-12 students enrolled in HSPS which is down about 25 students from the end of the 2019-20 school year. Our number of new students enrolled this year is consistent with what it has been in the past. The loss of students is mostly attributable due to a larger graduating class of seniors and a smaller incoming class of kindergarten students.

City of Harbor Springs
May 29 at 3:19 PM Â·

The Harbor Springs Police Department is nationally accredited by an organization identified as Commission on Accreditation for Law Enforcement Agencies (CALEA). An assessor from CALEA will be remotely assessing the Harbor Springs Police Department on June 1-June 2, 2020 to examine the Harbor Springs Police Departmentâ€™s policies, procedures and practices as they relate to the management and operation of the department and the delivery of police services. This remote on-site assessment takes the place of what would normally be an in person assessment which was not possible due to the COVID-19 Pandemic.

shared_text:
Meyer Ace Hardware
May 22 at 7:22 AM Â·

Help us honor our graduating seniors. We have hundreds of blue light bulbs in our Petoskey and Gaylord stores (Northmen, Blue Devils and Snowbird colors) and Orange Light bulbs in our Harbor Springs store (Rams). Here's what you do
1.) Pickup a light bulb with a minimum suggested donation of $1.
2.) Put the colored light bulb in your front porch fixture.
3.) Turn the light on at dark.
4.) Meyer Ace donates all funds raised from light bulbs back to the schools to help in areas where COVID-19 has negatively impacted their budget.

Thank you for your support!

#GlowForGrads #TheHelpfulPlace

Each year, Char-Em ISD hosts a banquet honoring students who have excelled in their Career and Technical Education programs. The banquet was planned to be held today, April 28, 2020. While we can't gather together, we still want to recognize the hard work of our students in their CTE programs! Students from HARBOR SPRINGS being recognized are:

Business Management and Administration: Abigail, Elijah , Gage, and Lance

Drafting and Design Technology: Sheridan, Isabelle, and Josh

Graphics and Printing Technology: Brooke and Kaycee

Woodworking and Furniture Making: Maggie, Jack, Cole, Jamison and Luke.

Jim Rummer, Director of Char-Em ISD's Career and Technical Education Department, also recorded a video message to the students; please watch it at this link:

post_text:
The first week of The Young Americans Performing Arts Summer Camps at Harbor Springs High School starts in less than two weeks. What are you waiting for?

Your student will spend four exhilarating days learning a fully-staged performance under the guidance of an amazing cast of 38 music ambassadors who are positive, energetic, engaging and uplifting. The week culminates in three shows for families, friends and the community where campers get to celebrate their talents and all of their accomplishments.

Donâ€™t let your student miss this opportunity to explore their creativity and be pushed to new limits! There are four weeks to choose from or just do them all! Some kids do!

Week 1 -- June 25-29: Take the Stage
Week 2 -- July 1-6: Best of Stage and Screen
Week 3 -- July 23-27: Take the Stage
Week 4 -- July 30- August 3: Best of Stage and Screen

Pick a week and register at youngamericans.org/summer-camps.

post_text: Harbor Springs Public Schools is pleased to announce that it will be hosting eight students and their teacher from the Bilingual Primary School of Luhe (Nanjing, China) from April 28-May 11, 2019. The fifth grade students will be visiting Harbor Springs for a â€œspring camp exchange and cultural experienceâ€ as part of a sister school relationship with Harbor Springs Public Schools. This partnership was formalized earlier in the school year. The main goals of the spring camp exchange will be to build connections, gain a greater sense of cultural awareness, and to learn about language, customs, and educational systems. According to superintendent of schools Michael Behrmann, â€œThis is an amazing opportunity for our students to experience a culture that is very different from ours in every sense. The students from Luhe Primary School will attend classes, go to lunch, experience recess, and engage in cooperative activities with the Shay students. We hope that students from both countries realize that people are people and kids are kids, no matter where they are from.â€

The Hoops for Troops basketball games will be played as scheduled on February 15, 2019. We will be honoring our local veterans, active military and high school kids who have enlisted in the armed services.

Boys & Girls varsity basketball will be playing against Traverse City St. Francis. Varsity Girls game starts at 5:30 PM, and the honoring of our veterans, along with the presentation of the color and Native drummers at 6:45 PM.

Bake sale and 50/50 raffle during the events with 100% of ALL proceeds going to Brave Heart Estates!

Show you Military ID and get into the game for free!
